column5: {50094: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50094",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1557",\\n    "Technique name": "Adversary-in-the-Middle",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to position themselves between two or more networked devices using an adversary-in-the-middle (AiTM) technique to support follow-on behaviors such as Network Sniffing, Transmitted Data Manipulation, or replay attacks (Exploitation for Credential Access)\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an HTTP attack attempt involving the Responder poisoner, which is a tool used for performing LLMNR/NBT-NS poisoning attacks. This type of attack involves positioning the attacker as a man-in-the-middle between the victim and a legitimate server, allowing them to intercept and manipulate network traffic, which aligns with the Adversary-in-the-Middle technique."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

This type of attack involves positioning the attacker as a man-in-the-middle between the victim and a legitimate server, allowing them to intercept and manipulate network traffic, which aligns with the Adversary-in-the-Middle technique."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {38563: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "38563",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1056",\\n    "Technique name": "Input Capture",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use methods of capturing user input to obtain credentials or collect information"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects activity related to the Win.Trojan.GateKeylogger malware, which is designed to capture user input such as keystrokes to steal sensitive information like credentials. column5: {1129: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "1129",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1083",\\n    "Technique name": "File and Directory Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may enumerate files and directories or may search in specific locations of a host or network share for certain information within a file system\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect attempts to access the .htaccess file, which is a configuration file used by Apache web servers to control access and behavior for specific directories. column5: {27967: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "27967",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects a web shell connection attempt, which is a type of malware that exploits vulnerabilities in public-facing web applications to gain initial access to the network."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "27967", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1105",\\n    "Technique name": "Ingress Tool Transfer",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may transfer tools or other files from an external system into a compromised environment\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for the transfer of a web shell tool (Chopper) from an external system to the compromised web server, which is a form of ingress tool transfer."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {29869: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "29869",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1566",\\n    "Technique name": "Phishing",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may send phishing messages to gain access to victim systems\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects a phishing attack by the Win.Trojan.Napolar malware, which likely involves sending malicious links or attachments disguised as legitimate content to trick users into executing the malware. column5: {31807: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "31807",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1041",\\n    "Technique name": "Exfiltration Over C2 Channel",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may steal data by exfiltrating it over an existing command and control channel\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects a Trojan (Win.Trojan.Nighthunter) attempting to exfiltrate data over an SMTP channel, which is a common command and control channel used by malware."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "31807", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1048",\\n    "Technique name": "Exfiltration Over Alternative Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may steal data by exfiltrating it over a different protocol than that of the existing command and control channel\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for data exfiltration attempts over SMTP, which is an alternative protocol to the typical HTTP/HTTPS channels used for command and control."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {56614: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56614",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect Cobalt Strike beacon traffic, which uses HTTP as an application layer protocol to blend in with normal web traffic and evade detection."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56614", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1573",\\n    "Technique name": "Encrypted Channel",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may employ a known encryption algorithm to conceal command and control traffic rather than relying on any inherent protections provided by a communication protocol\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule looks for the \\\'Accept-Encoding\\\' header, which is used by Cobalt Strike to indicate the use of encryption (gzip, deflate, br) for concealing command and control traffic."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56614",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1036",\\n    "Technique name": "Masquerading",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is designed to detect Cobalt Strike beacons, which masquerade as legitimate HTTP traffic by using specific URI paths (/v1/queue, /v1/profile, /v1/docs/wsdl, /v1/pull) to appear benign."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {47399: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "47399",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1059",\\n    "Technique name": "Command and Scripting Interpreter",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse command and script interpreters to execute commands, scripts, or binaries\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an outbound connection attempt from the cmd.exe command interpreter, which is commonly used by adversaries to execute malicious commands or scripts on compromised systems."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "47399",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1021",\\n    "Technique name": "Remote Services",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use Valid Accounts to log into a service that accepts remote connections, such as telnet, SSH, and VNC\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an outbound connection attempt, which could be an indicator of an adversary attempting to establish a remote connection to a compromised system using a valid account."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {44689: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "44689",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\\"Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\\""],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects outbound HTTP traffic to a specific URI path (/aspnet_client/system_web/4_0_30319/update/), which could be an attempt by malware to communicate with a command and control server using the application layer protocol HTTP to blend in with legitimate traffic."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "44689",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1102",\\n    "Technique name": "Web Service",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\\"Adversaries may use an existing, legitimate external Web service as a means for relaying data to/from a compromised system\\\\""],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for outbound HTTP traffic to a specific URI path, which could indicate that the malware is using a legitimate web service as a means to relay data from the compromised system to a command and control server."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {37313: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "37313",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1048",\\n    "Technique name": "Exfiltration Over Alternative Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may steal data by exfiltrating it over a different protocol than that of the existing command and control channel\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to exfiltrate data over the SMTP protocol, which is an alternative protocol to the typical command and control channel used by adversaries. column5: {49529: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "49529",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1557",\\n    "Technique name": "Adversary-in-the-Middle",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to position themselves between two or more networked devices using an adversary-in-the-middle (AiTM) technique to support follow-on behaviors such as Network Sniffing, Transmitted Data Manipulation, or replay attacks (Exploitation for Credential Access)\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects an attempt to download a \\\'poisoners.NBTNS\\\' file, which is likely related to a Responder tool used for performing LLMNR/NBT-NS poisoning attacks. column5: {60401: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "60401",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1505",\\n    "Technique name": "Server Software Component",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse legitimate extensible development features of servers to establish persistent access to systems\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects an inbound connection attempt to a PHP web shell named DToolPro, which is a malicious server software component that can be abused by adversaries to gain persistent access and execute commands on the compromised system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "60401", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1059",\\n    "Technique name": "Command and Scripting Interpreter",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse command and script interpreters to execute commands, scripts, or binaries\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule looks for the presence of \\\'?&cmd=\\\' in the HTTP request, which indicates an attempt to execute commands or scripts through the PHP web shell using a command and scripting interpreter."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {56601: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56601",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1608",\\n    "Technique name": "Stage Capabilities",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may upload, install, or otherwise set up capabilities that can be used during targeting\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to download a stager component (likely a malicious payload) from a remote server, which aligns with the Stage Capabilities technique where adversaries set up capabilities on a compromised system for further exploitation."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56601", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1102",\\n    "Technique name": "Web Service",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use an existing, legitimate external Web service as a means for relaying data to/from a compromised system\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects communication with a remote server over HTTP, which could be leveraging a legitimate web service to relay malicious data, corresponding to the Web Service technique."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56601",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1036",\\n    "Technique name": "Masquerading",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule mentions headers and content that mimic legitimate web traffic, suggesting an attempt to masquerade the malicious activity as benign, which aligns with the Masquerading technique."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column7: {56601: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56601",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1608",\\n    "Technique name": "Stage Capabilities",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may upload, install, or otherwise set up capabilities that can be used during targeting\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to download a stager component (likely a malicious payload) from a remote server, which aligns with the Stage Capabilities technique where adversaries set up capabilities on a compromised system for further exploitation."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56601", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1102",\\n    "Technique name": "Web Service",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use an existing, legitimate external Web service as a means for relaying data to/from a compromised system\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects communication with a remote server over HTTP, which could be leveraging a legitimate web service to relay malicious data, corresponding to the Web Service technique."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56601",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1036",\\n    "Technique name": "Masquerading",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule mentions headers and content that mimic legitimate web traffic, suggesting an attempt to masquerade the malicious activity as benign, which aligns with the Masquerading technique."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {50277: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50277",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1505",\\n    "Technique name": "Server Software Component",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse legitimate extensible development features of servers to establish persistent access to systems\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects an inbound request attempt to a specific URI (\\\'/temporary_listen_addresses/wsman\\\') which could be indicative of an adversary attempting to abuse a server software component (in this case, a webshell named \\\'Chopper\\\') to establish persistent access on the system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50277",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is designed to detect an inbound request attempt, which could be an attempt by an adversary to exploit a public-facing application (in this case, a webshell) to gain initial access to the network."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {30512: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "30512",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to exploit the OpenSSL TLSv1.1 heartbeat read overrun vulnerability (CVE-2014-0160) in public-facing servers running SSL/TLS services. This vulnerability could allow an adversary to remotely access and potentially gain unauthorized access to the targeted system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "30512", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1046",\\n    "Technique name": "Network Service Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to get a listing of services running on remote hosts and local network infrastructure devices, including those that may be vulnerable to remote software exploitation\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is triggered when the specific traffic pattern associated with the OpenSSL heartbeat exploit is detected on common SSL/TLS service ports (21, 25, 443, 465, 636, 992, 993, 995, 2484). This implies that the adversary is scanning for and attempting to identify vulnerable SSL/TLS services on the target network."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {1142: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "1142",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1046",\\n    "Technique name": "Network Service Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to get a listing of services running on remote hosts and local network infrastructure devices, including those that may be vulnerable to remote software exploitation\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect attempts to access the \\\'/....\\\' path on web servers, which could be an indication of an adversary trying to discover and enumerate running services or applications on the target system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "1142", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1083",\\n    "Technique name": "File and Directory Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may enumerate files and directories or may search in specific locations of a host or network share for certain information within a file system\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The \\\'/....\\\' path in the Snort rule could also be an attempt by an adversary to enumerate files and directories on the web server, which is a common technique used for reconnaissance and information gathering."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {56600: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56600",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is detecting outbound HTTP traffic from an infected host to an external network, which could be an attempt by malware to communicate with a command and control server using the application layer protocol HTTP. column5: {56598: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56598",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1090",\\n    "Technique name": "Proxy",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use a connection proxy to direct network traffic between systems or act as an intermediary for network communications to a command and control server to avoid direct connections to their infrastructure"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects an inbound connection attempt from an external network to the internal network, which could be indicative of a backdoor or command and control communication using a proxy to obfuscate the source of the traffic."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56598",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1573",\\n    "Technique name": "Encrypted Channel",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may employ a known encryption algorithm to conceal command and control traffic rather than relying on any inherent protections provided by a communication protocol"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule looks for specific content in the HTTP traffic, which could be an indication of encrypted or obfuscated data being transmitted as part of a command and control communication."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {41435: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "41435",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1197",\\n    "Technique name": "BITS Jobs",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse BITS jobs to persistently execute code and perform various background tasks\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects a malware variant (Win.Trojan.Oilrig) that uses the Background Intelligent Transfer Service (BITS) to establish an outbound connection, likely for command and control purposes. column5: {32043: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "32043",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1059",\\n    "Technique name": "Command and Scripting Interpreter",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse command and script interpreters to execute commands, scripts, or binaries\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to inject malicious code into a Bash environment variable, which is a form of command and script interpreter abuse. The rule looks for the pattern \\\'() {\\\' in the USER command of an FTP session, which could be used to execute arbitrary commands on the server."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "32043", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1202",\\n    "Technique name": "Indirect Command Execution",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse utilities that allow for command execution to bypass security restrictions that limit the use of command-line interpreters\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is also related to Indirect Command Execution, as the attacker is attempting to execute commands indirectly by injecting code into an environment variable, which could bypass restrictions on direct command execution."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {35471: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n    {\\n        "sid": "35471",\\n        "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n        "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n        "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n        "Explanation": "The Snort rule is detecting outbound HTTP traffic to a specific URL (/9hao/count.asp) on port 6666, which suggests the use of an application layer protocol (HTTP) for command and control communication by the Baisogu malware."\\n    },\\n    {\\n        "sid": "35471",\\n        "Technique ID": "T1090",\\n        "Technique name": "Proxy",\\n        "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use a connection proxy to direct network traffic between systems or act as an intermediary for network communications to a command and control server to avoid direct connections to their infrastructure\\\'"],\\n        "Explanation": "The rule is looking for outbound connections to an external IP address on port 6666, which could potentially be a proxy server used by the malware to communicate with its command and control infrastructure indirectly."\\n    },\\n    {\\n        "sid": "35471",\\n        "Technique ID": "T1001",\\n        "Technique name": "Data Obfuscation",\\n        "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may obfuscate command and control traffic to make it more difficult to detect\\\'"],\\n        "Explanation": "The rule is looking for specific parameters in the HTTP request (?mac=, ?ver=, ?tjuser=), which could be an attempt by the malware to obfuscate or encode data within the command and control traffic to evade detection."\\n    }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {34037: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "34037",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1036",\\n    "Technique name": "Masquerading",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects a Trojan (Win.Trojan.Dridex4) that attempts to masquerade its initial outbound connection by including a \\\'Referer: https://twitter.com/\\\' header, which is a technique used by malware to appear as legitimate web traffic."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "34037", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for HTTP traffic, which is an application layer protocol, indicating that the Trojan is using this protocol to communicate and blend in with normal web traffic."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {50463: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50463",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1003",\\n    "Technique name": "OS Credential Dumping",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to dump credentials to obtain account login and credential material, normally in the form of a hash or a clear text password, from the operating system and software\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to use the Mimikatz tool, which is commonly used for credential dumping on Windows systems. The rule specifically looks for the \\\'kuhl_m_lsadump_getHash\\\' string, which is a Mimikatz command used to extract password hashes from the Local Security Authority (LSA) process memory."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {60299: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "60299",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1505",\\n    "Technique name": "Server Software Component",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse legitimate extensible development features of servers to establish persistent access to systems\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to upload a PHP webshell named \\\'Cybershell\\\', which is a type of malicious server software component that can provide persistent access to the compromised system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "60299", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1105",\\n    "Technique name": "Ingress Tool Transfer",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may transfer tools or other files from an external system into a compromised environment\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for the upload of the \\\'Cybershell\\\' webshell, which is a tool being transferred from an external system to the compromised web server."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {27756: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "27756",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects an attempt to exploit a vulnerability in the RedHat Piranha Virtual Server Package, which is a public-facing web application, by trying to access the passwd.php3 script with the \\\'passwd=ACCEPT\\\' parameter to potentially execute arbitrary commands or gain unauthorized access."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "27756", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1059",\\n    "Technique name": "Command and Scripting Interpreter",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse command and script interpreters to execute commands, scripts, or binaries\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for an attempt to execute arbitrary commands or scripts by exploiting a vulnerability in the RedHat Piranha Virtual Server Package, which would involve abusing a command or scripting interpreter."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {32105: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "32105",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1203",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Client Execution",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may exploit software vulnerabilities in client applications to execute code\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to exploit a vulnerability in the Oracle WebCenter Content CheckOutAndOpen.dll ActiveX control, which could allow an adversary to execute arbitrary code on the client system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "32105", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1176",\\n    "Technique name": "Browser Extensions",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse Internet browser extensions to establish persistent access to victim systems\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for indicators related to the exploitation of an ActiveX control, which is a type of browser extension that can be abused by adversaries to gain persistent access or execute code on the client system."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {32771: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "32771",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1566",\\n    "Technique name": "Phishing",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may send phishing messages to gain access to victim systems\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects a phishing attempt where an email with a malicious attachment disguised as an Adobe invoice is sent, likely to trick users into opening the attachment and compromising their systems."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "32771", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1598",\\n    "Technique name": "Phishing for Information",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may send phishing messages to elicit sensitive information that can be used during targeting\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The phishing email may be an attempt to gather information from the victim, such as credentials or other sensitive data, by tricking them into opening the malicious attachment."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {25579: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "25579",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1566",\\n    "Technique name": "Phishing",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may send phishing messages to gain access to victim systems\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects a phishing attack where a malicious file named \\\'BookingInfo.zip\\\' is delivered, likely through a phishing email or message, to trick the victim into executing the malware \\\'BookingInfo.exe\\\'."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "25579", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1036",\\n    "Technique name": "Masquerading",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule suggests that the malware is masquerading as a legitimate \\\'BookingInfo.zip\\\' file, which is a technique used by adversaries to make their malicious artifacts appear benign to users."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {38562: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "38562",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1020",\\n    "Technique name": "Automated Exfiltration",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\\"Adversaries may exfiltrate data, such as sensitive documents, through the use of automated processing after being gathered during Collection\\\\""],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects an initial exfiltration attempt by the GateKeylogger malware, which is likely to automate the process of sending captured data (such as keystrokes) to a remote command and control server."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "38562", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1056",\\n    "Technique name": "Input Capture",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\\"Adversaries may use methods of capturing user input to obtain credentials or collect information\\\\""],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is specifically designed to detect the GateKeylogger malware, which is a type of keylogger that captures user input (such as keystrokes) to obtain sensitive information like credentials."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {50465: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50465",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1557",\\n    "Technique name": "Adversary-in-the-Middle",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to position themselves between two or more networked devices using an adversary-in-the-middle (AiTM) technique to support follow-on behaviors such as Network Sniffing, Transmitted Data Manipulation, or replay attacks (Exploitation for Credential Access)\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to perform an SMB negotiation attack using the Responder tool, which is a type of adversary-in-the-middle attack. column5: {57462: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "57462",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1505",\\n    "Technique name": "Server Software Component",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\\"Adversaries may abuse legitimate extensible development features of servers to establish persistent access to systems\\\\""],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects a variant of the STEADYPULSE webshell, which is a malicious server software component that allows adversaries to gain persistent access and execute commands on the compromised system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "57462", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1059",\\n    "Technique name": "Command and Scripting Interpreter",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\\"Adversaries may abuse command and script interpreters to execute commands, scripts, or binaries\\\\""],\\n    "Explanation": "The webshell detected by the Snort rule likely uses a command or scripting interpreter (e.g., Perl) to execute arbitrary commands on the compromised system."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {48231: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "48231",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1220",\\n    "Technique name": "XSL Script Processing",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may bypass application control and obscure execution of code by embedding scripts inside XSL files\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to inject malicious XSL code into the Apache Syncope web application, which aligns with the XSL Script Processing technique used by adversaries to bypass application controls and execute malicious code."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "48231", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is designed to detect an exploit attempt against the public-facing Apache Syncope web application, which is consistent with the Exploit Public-Facing Application technique used by adversaries to gain initial access to a network."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {19706: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "19706",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects outbound HTTP traffic from a compromised host to an external server, which could be an attempt by malware to communicate using the application layer protocol HTTP to blend in with normal web traffic and avoid detection."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "19706",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1102",\\n    "Technique name": "Web Service",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use an existing, legitimate external Web service as a means for relaying data to/from a compromised system\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule specifically looks for a URI (\\\'/com_plugin.php\\\') that could be used by malware to communicate with an external web service, potentially for relaying data or receiving commands."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {57466: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "57466",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1090",\\n    "Technique name": "Proxy",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\\"Adversaries may use a connection proxy to direct network traffic between systems or act as an intermediary for network communications to a command and control server to avoid direct connections to their infrastructure\\\\""],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects inbound connections to a CGI script (/compcheckresult.cgi) that may be used as a proxy or intermediary for command and control communications by the Perl.Backdoor.ATRIUM malware variant."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "57466",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\\"Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\\""],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for HTTP traffic, which is an application layer protocol, potentially used by the malware to blend in with legitimate traffic and avoid detection."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {24426: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n    {\\n        "sid": "24426",\\n        "Technique ID": "T1105",\\n        "Technique name": "Ingress Tool Transfer",\\n        "Quotes": ["\\\\"MALWARE-OTHER Java.Trojan.Jacksbot class download\\\\""],\\n        "Explanation": "The rule detects the download of a malicious Java class file, which is a technique used by adversaries to transfer tools or other files from an external system into a compromised environment."\\n    },\\n    {\\n        "sid": "24426", \\n        "Technique ID": "T1083",\\n        "Technique name": "File and Directory Discovery",\\n        "Quotes": ["\\\\"content:\\\'.minecraft\\\',distance 0; content:\\\'/etc/rc.common\\\',distance 0; content:\\\'/etc/rc.local\\\',distance 0; content:\\\'.filezilla/recentservers.xml\\\',distance 0;\\\\""],\\n        "Explanation": "The rule looks for specific file paths and directories, which indicates that the malware is attempting to enumerate files and directories on the compromised system, a technique used by adversaries for file and directory discovery."\\n    }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {23612: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "23612",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1221",\\n    "Technique name": "Template Injection",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may create or modify references in user document templates to conceal malicious code or force authentication attempts\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to embed malicious JavaScript code within an XML template in a PDF file, which aligns with the Template Injection technique where adversaries modify document templates to conceal malicious code."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "23612", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1027",\\n    "Technique name": "Obfuscated Files or Information",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to make an executable or file difficult to discover or analyze by encrypting, encoding, or otherwise obfuscating its contents on the system or in transit\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for obfuscated JavaScript code embedded within an XML template in a PDF file, which could be an attempt by an adversary to obfuscate malicious code or information within a legitimate file format."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {46067: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "46067",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1176",\\n    "Technique name": "Browser Extensions",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse Internet browser extensions to establish persistent access to victim systems\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects a Trojan downloader that communicates with an external server, potentially using a browser extension as a persistence mechanism. column5: {41084: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "41084",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1189",\\n    "Technique name": "Drive-by Compromise",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may gain access to a system through a user visiting a website over the normal course of browsing\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect the landing page of the Sundown Exploit Kit, which is used to deliver malware through drive-by download attacks. The rule looks for obfuscated JavaScript code that is commonly used by exploit kits to fingerprint the victim\\\'s system and deliver the appropriate exploit."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "41084", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1203",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Client Execution",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may exploit software vulnerabilities in client applications to execute code\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Sundown Exploit Kit leverages vulnerabilities in client applications like web browsers to execute malicious code on the victim\\\'s system. The obfuscated JavaScript detected by the rule is likely used to identify and exploit vulnerabilities in the client application."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "41084",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1027",\\n    "Technique name": "Obfuscated Files or Information",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to make an executable or file difficult to discover or analyze by encrypting, encoding, or otherwise obfuscating its contents on the system or in transit\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule specifically looks for obfuscated JavaScript code, which is a common technique used by exploit kits to hide their malicious functionality from detection and analysis."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {48501: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "48501",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1485",\\n    "Technique name": "Data Destruction",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may destroy data and files on specific systems or in large numbers on a network to interrupt availability to systems, services, and network resources\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects the download of a malicious tool that contains the command \\\'/q & & shutdown /r /f /t 000\\\', which is used to forcibly reboot the system, potentially leading to data destruction or interruption of system availability."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "48501", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1105",\\n    "Technique name": "Ingress Tool Transfer",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may transfer tools or other files from an external system into a compromised environment\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect the download of a malicious tool from an external source, which aligns with the Ingress Tool Transfer technique used by adversaries to introduce malicious tools into a compromised environment."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}
